name: Man
phrases_kaytetye: Artweye nyarte apenkerne atyenge angkewethe, akngke ampilewethe, akngke apeke.
phrases_english: That man is coming to talk to me maybe to tell me something.

name: Woman
phrases_kaytetye: Arelhe nthewarte ayenge angkewethawe, atye apeke artntwewethe kwere arntwewe apeke katye ilewethe atyenge.
phrases_english: I want to ask that woman over there to see if she can get some water for me.

name: Car
phrases_kaytetye: Mweteke nthelarte aynanthe apewenawe, alwengayewene aynewanthe iterrtye. Angketye aynanthe arlengarle alpeyenteyanemeketye.
phrases_english: Let's ask that person if they can take us in the car, its too far to walk.

name: Bush car
phrases_kaytetye: Mweteke atyeyenge arntenhe. Nyartepe errpatyarrenhe, tyre tyampe atyeyenge wanterteyange nhangarteye, errpatyarrenhe.
phrases_english: My car is not working, the tyres are no good, and something else is broken.

name: Bush bus
phrases_kaytetye: Ngke, marntele aynanthe alpewene nharte aynanthe arntyarrtyewene stopem-ayleme.
phrases_english: Stop the bus so we can go back on it.

name: Footy
phrases_kaytetye: Pweltye aynanthe ape nywerrpe inengele aynanthe play arreranewetheye, nywerrpe-nywerrepele.
phrases_english: We used to play traditional football with teams of different skin groups.

name: Swag
phrases_kaytetye: Pantye arrene tyangkwerre atyengawe, atnkwe ayenge enwewethe.
phrases_english: Put the swag down this way for me so I can sleep.

name: Hat
phrases_kaytetye: Mwekarte etnyewenawe, elye, elye.
phrases_english: Give me a hat for shade.

name: Fire
phrases_kaytetye: Ware nyarte arrpewenawe, wante ngayele aynewethe apeke, atnwenthe arlewatyerre.
phrases_english: Let's light a fire, as we want to eat some food, cook this goanna meat.

name: Ashes
phrases_kaytetye: Arlpe rteye atyenge etnyewenawe, ayengepe apeyake arlpewe, tyanywengepe atye atherrke aynewethe.
phrases_english: Can you give me some ashes? I dont have any, just so I can mix it with my tobacco to chew.

name: Billy can
phrases_kaytetye: Tyampete atyenge etnyewene arntwe apeke atye ilewethe, teye apeke atye kwathewethe.
phrases_english: Give me a billycan so I can get some water or make tea to drink.

name: Country / place
phrases_kaytetye: Apmere atyeyenge nharte althewenawe, ayenge atnkwe enwewethe, pantyarrangele tyampe.
phrases_english: Clean the area there so I can put the swag down and sleep.

name: Boomerang
phrases_kaytetye: Kayle atyenge nharte etnyewenawe! Elkwatherre atyenge apekarle ahenge alweye.
phrases_english: Give me that boomerang, for protection from someone who might be looking to fight me.

name: Digging stick
phrases_kaytetye: Atneme atyenge nharte etnyewenawe! Pwenge inenge angkerle, 'Atneme atyenge nharte etnyewenawe, ayenge atyangkwerre apewene alewatyerre apeke alarrewethe.'
phrases_english: Give me that yamstick, an old lady might say, I want to go for a walk and look around for some goanna.

name: Shield
phrases_kaytetye: Aheketye apeke aynewenhanthe aylkewethe etnyewene atyenge karlarte nhartepe, awe lhangkalewe apeke (?) nhartepe akngke aynanthe aylewethe.
phrases_english: Give me that shield, so we can protect ourselves in the fight. We also use a shield in our ceremonies.

name: Woman dancing
phrases_kaytetye: Awelye rrkante artnwenge nyangarte tyampe akaltyinewethe alkenharengele,  akaltyarreranewethe re, awelye  nthelarte.
phrases_english: Get the women to teach the children their ceremonies, the children need to grow up learning these things.

name: Men's dance
phrases_kaytetye: Lthartewe aynanthe cleanemayleye, elyakerre mpwarene aynanthe rlengke etnherranewethe, lthartelke aynanthe iterrtye inenge akarreranewethe atnkwarengele, atwerrpele arlenge aylerantyewethe.
phrases_english: Today we will prepare the ceremony ground for tonight and make a shade structure. People will gather here for the ceremony tonight, or in the late afternoon to start the singing.

name: Heart
phrases_kaytetye: Anaty-anatye ayenge a little bit errpatyawe, amperrane ayenge anaty-anatyepe.
phrases_english: My heart is not quite right, my heart is burning.

name: Aboriginal flag
phrases_kaytetye: Awe nyarte, aynewantheyenge nhartepe errpwerle inenge arenge flag-pe atanthe mpwarenhe. Iterrtyarenge.
phrases_english: This is our Aboriginal flag design. It belongs to Aboriginal people.

name: Hand
phrases_kaytetye: Tywekere arrenke aynanthe mpelarte, eltye atyenge arene, tywekere arreranenke aynanthe!
phrases_english: We dont like it, see how Im waving my hand, that means we dont like it or want to do it.

name: What's up?
phrases_kaytetye: Nthakenhe nge apenkawe anteyanawe, nthakenhe arrenkepe? Ayengepe anteyane rtame.
phrases_english: What do you want to do, are you coming or staying? No I'll stay.

name: No
phrases_kaytetye: Ye peyakele rtamawe. Ye peyakele mentye.
phrases_english: Nothing, leave it.

name: Hungry
phrases_kaytetye: Ngayele ayenge nyartepe, aperrane etnthwerrane ngayelewe etnyewethe apeke atyenge.
phrases_english: I'm hungry now, I'm walking around hoping someone might give me some food.

name: Talk
phrases_kaytetye: Angkene nge atyenge wentarawe, atyenge ntethe ampilene, wentararle ntethe ampilene, atnhante amernele arlenge althilerantyengarle?
phrases_english: Tell me, speak up loud and tell me about who is fighting.

name: Liar
phrases_kaytetye: Nhartepe ntelhanteyane rtame. Tewene errwanthe nharte elpathewethe nthelaperte ntelhanteyane.
phrases_english: Don't listen to him he is telling lies.

name: Dislike
phrases_kaytetye: Tywekere arrenke aynanthe mpelarte, eltye atyenge arene, tywekere arrenke aynanthe!
phrases_english: We dont like it, see how I'm waving, that means we dont like it or want to do it.

name: Quiet
phrases_kaytetye: Akerlitarrene ngawe! Tewene angkewethe wentare, akerlitarrene nge!
phrases_english: Be quiet don't say anything, don't say it loud, stay quiet.

name: Today
phrases_kaytetye: Rlengke ayenge aperrernenyeye rtame.
phrases_english: I'm coming today.

name: Father
phrases_kaytetye: Arlweye rteye atyengaye, nthekangkwerre repe? Awe, arrenye re apenhe arlelke apewethe.
phrases_english: Where's my father? Oh he's gone hunting over there.

name: Older brother
phrases_kaytetye: Kakeye rteye atyeyenge?
phrases_english: Where’s my big brother?

name: Mother's father
phrases_kaytetye: Atyewaleye rteye atyeyenge? Rwengkawe, nharte re entweyane arntetye.
phrases_english: Where is my grandfather (mother's father)? Not sure, there he is lying down sick.

name: Younger sibling
phrases_kaytetye: Atyerreye atyenge rteye? Nyarte atyeyenge atyerreye rteye? Nthekangkwerre re aytnarrenhe. Rwengke re apenhawe.
phrases_english: Where did my younger brother go? He's gone somewhere. I don't know where he went.

name: Nephew, niece
phrases_kaytetye: Artwaleye atyeyenge rteye? Nyartepe, artwaleye atyeyenge.
phrases_english: Wheres my sister's child? The handsign for which is like this.

name: Female cousin
phrases_kaytetye: Altyeleye rteye atyeyengaye? Aytnarrenhelke re. 'Rwengke re apelapenhe'.
phrases_english: Where did my cousin just disappear to? 'I don't know, she went somewhere.'

name: Spouse, Brother-in-law
phrases_kaytetye: Nharteye, mpwerneye, you gotta atyenge arrkare rteye?
phrases_english: Hey brother-in-law where is your sister, my wife.

name: Mother's mother
phrases_kaytetye: Nyanye rteye atyeyenge? Nthekangkwerre aparte aytnarrelhaytenye. No arnpatyarrenhe re, aynewanthe ketye eletnhelaytenye, altherarrengele.
phrases_english: Where's my grandmother? I dont know she felt lonely and just left us and went somewhere.

name: Wait
phrases_kaytetye: Ye alelaperte nge anenawe! Alelaperte ayenge etarrengele alwene apertame.
phrases_english: You wait here for a while; I'll think about it and come back.

name: Policeman
phrases_kaytetye: Pwertaye, nthelarte aynewanthe arntarrtyemeketye, eltyemwerneyele.
phrases_english: Watch out there is a policeman there, he might grab us!

name: Handful of dirt
phrases_kaytetye: Ye, ahernepe nyarte aynewantheyenge.
phrases_english: This is our ground (country).

name: Footprints
phrases_kaytetye: Tyelartaye, kwenyele apeke awatnkaperte tyelaperte angketye amperlanpanenhe.
phrases_english: Right here, there’s some tracks which might have been made yesterday or a few days ago.

name: Kangaroo tracks
phrases_kaytetye: Ye aherr-arengepe aynanthe, amperl-arenke rtame.
phrases_english: We can follow these kangaroo tracks.

name: People sitting
phrases_kaytetye: Nhartepe erlkwe inenge anteyane lhangkelewe. Lhangkele anteyanewethe artnwengewe aylerantyewe.
phrases_english: The old men are sitting down over there getting ready for business, to sing the ceremony for young men.

name: Rain, Water
phrases_kaytetye: Ntyerrele arntwe.
phrases_english: Water is also called ‘ntyerrele’.

name: Sun
phrases_kaytetye: Aherrke-ketye ayenge anteyanawe, ileke-ketye ayenge anteyane, angketye aherrkele ayenge ampeketye.
phrases_english: I'm sitting down because of the prickles and because of the sun which is too hot, my feet might burn.

name: Cloud
phrases_kaytetye: Mataye, nyarte aynanthe ayerrere theye erlwarerrantye, awe kngerrake theye apeke, mataye nyartepe apeyayterane, arntwe alkenhe apeke atntheyetnyewethe.
phrases_english: I can see the rain clouds are coming from the north and the east. We might get a big rain storm.

name: Morning star
phrases_kaytetye: Arene errwanthawe! Kngerrake erlwayteye kwerralye erltwe.
phrases_english: Hey look over there in the east, the morning star will rise!

name: Milky way
phrases_kaytetye: Ye, Mwererre errwele nharte! Nharte arenawe! Nharte nte arene errwelepe. Mwererre rtame nhartepe atyene artntwerantyene, nte apeke etelarerrantyewethe tneyele akerre.
phrases_english: Look up there, see that, that's what we call the Milky Way. Im telling you this so you will remember it.

name: Seven Sisters
phrases_kaytetye: Nharte errwanthe arenawe, Enterrke nharte atye showem-aylerantye errwele nharte nte arene, Enterrkepe.
phrases_english: Look up you mob, that's the Seven Sisters, I'm showing you.

name: Burning foot
phrases_kaytetye: Aherrke-ketye ayenge anteyanawe, ileke-ketye ayenge anteyane, angketye aherrkele ayenge ampeketye.
phrases_english: I'm sitting down because of the prickles and because of the sun which is too hot, my feet might burn.

name: Whirly wind
phrases_kaytetye: Pwertaye! Rarre aynewanthe alarremeketye awerantyerrenge nharte apeyayterane aherne impentyele.
phrases_english: Look out for that whirly wind coming; it might throw dirt and dust towards us.

name: Running water
phrases_kaytetye: Alenye nharte apeyayterane ketye antekerre theye, ayerrere theye apeke alenye ntheketyarte aynanthe arewene.
phrases_english: That flood water is coming from the south, or maybe the north. Let's have a look.

name: Morning
phrases_kaytetye: Ngwetyanpe nhartepe erlwaytenke kwerralye Erltwepe.
phrases_english: Thats where the Morning Star rises in the morning.

name: Midday
phrases_kaytetye: Artenyele nyartepe alkerele errwelarrenhele. Artentyele.
phrases_english: It's midday the sun is directly above us.

name: Late afternoon
phrases_kaytetye: Aherrke nyarte atnywerrane atwerrparrerane.
phrases_english: The sun is going down, it's late afternoon.

name: Night-time
phrases_kaytetye: Atnkwarengele aynanthe alpewenawe!
phrases_english: Let's go its nighttime.

name: Kangaroo tail
phrases_kaytetye: Aherre nyarte kantye rlwarrinewene aynanthe pwewethe.
phrases_english: Here's the kangaroo tail, remind us to cook it.

name: Native Currant
phrases_kaytetye: Ahakeyewe aynanthe apewenawe, ilewethe elkwemene inengepe angkeyayne ahakeyewelke.
phrases_english: Let's go and get native currants, the old ladies said.

name: Yam
phrases_kaytetye: Anatyewe aynanthe apewenawe, arrenye nyarte arrere aperte aynanthe apewene kngerrake.
phrases_english: Let's go for yams, just there close by, to the east.

name: Bush plum
phrases_kaytetye: Nkwerleye aynanthe aynewethe, elpayarle aynanthe apewene.
phrases_english: Let's go and pick bush plums from the trees down at the creek.

name: Dogwood seeds
phrases_kaytetye: Ntyerrme inengepe rntwenke akine kngwerele amerne rntwenke akine mpwarerrantyewethe aynterantyewethe arntwe warle atnhantinengele.
phrases_english: Everybody picks dogwood seeds, you can mix them in water when they are dry and eat them.

name: Split-jack
phrases_kaytetye: Rlwene alwerre. Rlwene atwakeye apenye wele akelye rtame. Artntele anteyane ante arlpawele sometimes.
phrases_english: The split jack tree has an edible fruit. It is like a bush orange but smaller. It can be found in the hills and sometimes on the plains.

name: Bush tomato
phrases_kaytetye: Tyangkwerre aynanthe apenkawe, arlkerre aynewethe. Wetharle aynanthe apmere kwerarlaperte elpatewarle alpewene.
phrases_english: Let's go to where the bush tomotoes are in the burnt country, that same place we always find them.

name: Wild Orange
phrases_kaytetye: Atwakeye nharte aynanthe aynewethe, nhartepe arletye aperte twematye etyerranepe.
phrases_english: We want to eat the bush oranges, but they are all still hanging there unripe.

name: Bush onion
phrases_kaytetye: Nthekangkwerre errwanthepe apenke? Na, nyarte aynanthe apenkarle. Ayerrere ltemarle apeke yerrakwerrewe wenhe.
phrases_english: Where are you mob going?' 'No we are just going to the north or maybe west to get bush onions.'

name: Tobacco
phrases_kaytetye: Tyanywenge atyenge etnyewenawe! Wantewe arre, tyanywenge aynewethe ilwekerele, etnyewene atyenge.
phrases_english: Give me some tobacco, I want to chew some tobacco please!

name: Snake
phrases_kaytetye: Apmwe rtame kngweranthelkepe etne, kngweranthelkepe etne wanenye rtame.
phrases_english: Some snakes don't have names (only those one's with a name have a story).

name: Euro
phrases_kaytetye: Arinenge nyarte artntenge errwele anteyane. Etnteyele nharte elye nthelarte apeke re anteyane.
phrases_english: Look at that euro sitting down on top of the rock. It might live in the cave or in the shade.

name: Honey ant
phrases_kaytetye: Wetharlarte alpenke same one warle apmere warle yerrampe aynanthe ilerantye angkwerre, ntharlarte aynanthe alpewene.
phrases_english: We will go back to that same place to get honeyants.

name: Ringneck parrot
phrases_kaytetye: Ye, arlpatye nhartepe apmelerre aperrane ilwekere akerrane, atnwenthe akine repe nharteye arlpatyepe, aynewethepe.
phrases_english: Ringneck parrots always fly around here. They are meat.

name: Thorny Devil
phrases_kaytetye: Arnkerrthepe nyartepe, nthekangkwerre re alpeyenteyane? Awe tyangkwerre ltemarle ngayelewe enthwelpenthwenke, arnkerrthepe.
phrases_english: Which way is that thorny devil going? Oh it's going west, looking around for food.

name: Possum
phrases_kaytetye: Wampere aynanthe ayneyayne atnwenthe atanthe awatnkakerre, aynewanthe wanenyele.
phrases_english: In the olden days we ate possum, before I was born.

name: Bilby
phrases_kaytetye: Artnangkelepe atnyemayte apmeyayne. Wenhe ltemarle amperle Merlentye angkwerre amperlanteyayne.
phrases_english: Bilbies dig for witchetty grubs. You can find them west of Five-Mile, around there.

name: Curlew
phrases_kaytetye: Pwertaye, ilere-ketye, nthelartepe aynewanthepe atnhante interarlwerantye re, arntetyaylemeketye.
phrases_english: Watch out, there’s a curlew, its following us and might make us sick.

name: Caterpillar
phrases_kaytetye: Ayepaytepe nhartepe apmelerre rtame aperrane.
phrases_english: Caterpillers can be found everywhere.

name: Butterfly
phrases_kaytetye: Ntelyapelyape nharte artnperr-entweyane arntwarle karrarrerane.
phrases_english: The butterflies are flittering and gathering around the water.

name: Tawny Frogmouth
phrases_kaytetye: Enwenengke nharte atnkwarengele angkerrane ketye, ilperele. Ilpere arenye rtame re enwenengkepe angkerrane.
phrases_english: The tawny frogmouth calls out at night from its hollow tree. It lives in a hollow tree.

name: Magpie / Butcherbird
phrases_kaytetye: Rrpwere nharte angkerrane ketye, ipmarrerantye aynewanthe rrpwerelepe.
phrases_english: Look out that magpie is telling us off.

name: Emu
phrases_kaytetye: Tyelartaye, atnhelengkwepe amperlanpanenhe. Tyangkwerre nawe, arntwepe kwatheyayne, tyangkwerre apewene enthwelp-enthwene. Tyewarlartepe kwatheyayne tneyele ayenge ngwenge akerre aperrernenyewethe.
phrases_english: Here look, this is an emu track it went past there to drink water. Let's go and keep looking for him over there. Oh he's been drinking here! We'll come back and look for it in the morning.

name: Boobook Owl
phrases_kaytetye: Pwerlerrngepe atnkwarengele 'tyangkwerre nthepele angkenke, pwerlerrngepe'. Nyarte kwereyenge ilperepe kwerelarle angkerranepe.
phrases_english: That boobook owl is always calling at night from over there. Calling from that hollow tree over there.

name: Bluetongue Lizard
phrases_kaytetye: Kangkere aynanthe aynewethawe!
phrases_english: Let's eat the bluetongue lizard.

name: Galah
phrases_kaytetye: Kelelkelelke nhartepe aperrane ilwekerane, apmere arrpanenhe arle.
phrases_english: Galahs go everywhere, poor things.

name: Fairy-wren
phrases_kaytetye: Pwertaye lyerre-lyerre nharte apenke anye angkelp-angkenke.
phrases_english: Hey someone must be here, that little fairy wren is flying past and telling us something.

name: Spotted Quoll
phrases_kaytetye: Atyertepe nhape atnwenthe aynewantheyenge. Tyangkwe nthepele atyerte inengepe anteyane, Rtwerrpe angkwerre, apewene aynanthe ape. Car-we angketyewe apeke, alarrewethelke aynanthe.
phrases_english: The spotted quoll is meat, they are around Redbank. Let's go and see if there are any tracks there and we might find one then.

name: Perentie
phrases_kaytetye: Atywetnpe tyangkwerre aynanthe — tyelartaye! Apenhe ampilpilewene aynanthepe atywetnpepe. Tyelartepange apenhe. Nyartepange arwelele etyerrane.
phrases_english: We'll follow this perentie's track . We'll follow it this way. It went this way. Oh it's here up in the tree.

name: Wedge-tailed Eagle
phrases_kaytetye: Ilpertenye aperrane atnwenthe wethewe ilwekere, nharte aherrewethewe aperrane arerr-apinterantye errwele theye.
phrases_english: There's a wedge-tailed eagle flying high above looking down for meat, maybe for kangaroo.

name: Death Adder
phrases_kaytetye: Mantharre ntheketyartawe, tewene kwere errwatewethe kantyele rtame mpwarlepe arrtyenke errtywernepe peyakele rtame.
phrases_english: Look out for the death adder, don't step on it, as it has a barb on its tail, but no poison in its teeth.

name: Dog
phrases_kaytetye: Aleke wayltake nhartepe aperrane, atnwenthe wethewe etnthwerrane, ilwekere.
phrases_english: That dingo is looking around for food, the poor thing.

name: Cheeky dog
phrases_kaytetye: Aleke inenge nhartepe awelengke — mpa, aynanthe anpatyarrewene, atnheme aynewanthe.
phrases_english: They are cheeky dogs, let's go before they attack us.

name: Fall in love
phrases_kaytetye: Nyarte ayenge mpwenyarrerane, nyartele aperranewethe. Nyartepe atyenge arelhe atnawerre atyengarle aperretnyewene, ayenge kwere mpwenyarrerane.
phrases_english: I'm falling in love with that person, she is the right skin for me, she might come to me or I might go to that girl.

name: Laugh
phrases_kaytetye: Atnhantewe nge rrkantarrenkepe. Na, nyartele atyenge nywerrpele atyenge angkerranele atyenge rrkantel-eletnheyayne etnyerrantye.
phrases_english: Who are you laughing at? No, it's that joker who's making me laugh.

name: Thinking
phrases_kaytetye: Alelaperte ayenge etarrengele alwene apertame.
phrases_english: Wait a minute, let me think back.

name: Swearing
phrases_kaytetye: Nthelartepe atyenge rtame ipmarrerantye wantepenherteyange? Just layeke ayenge kwereyenge ahewepenhe aperte atyengepe ipmarrerantye.
phrases_english: What is he growling at me about? It's not as if I've been giving him cheek.

name: Sad
phrases_kaytetye: Ayenge nthewartepe athamarrerane, nthewarteye iterrtyewe ayenge athamarrerane ilwekerewe.
phrases_english: I'm feeling sorry for that person, poor thing. I feel sad for them.

name: Healer
phrases_kaytetye: Ngangkaye ntethe arenawe, tyangkwerre ayenge artnweyenteyane aleme angkwerre, atnentye angkwerre apeke awe, tyarlenye nyarte atyenge ape arewene, ngangkayele.
phrases_english: Traditional healer, can you see the cause of the pain? I have a pain in my stomach, my throat and in my arm. Traditional healer can you check me?

name: Sick
phrases_kaytetye: Awe ye, ayengepe arntetye arrenhe, nyartepe entweyane.
phrases_english: Yes, I got sick, that's why I'm lying down.

name: Money-hungry
phrases_kaytetye: Ngkweltyewe nyartepe etarrerane ngkweltye apeke nthelarte atyenge etnyewethe.
phrases_english: That person might be thinking about giving me money.

name: Snoring
phrases_kaytetye: Atnkwe ayenge enwenhe ilwekerele atye pwerrketnheyayne penhe. Rarle ayenge atyewarrelke arrelp-arrenhe.
phrases_english: Dear me I was asleep snoring! But now I've woken up.

name: Spew
phrases_kaytetye: Erlkwetharrenhawe, apale atye atnwenthe aynenye, something ntweperte apeke, nharte ayenge erlkwetharrenhelke, amenge impentye apeke atye aynenye.
phrases_english: I'm going to vomit because unwittingly I ate something bad, maybe the meat was flyblown.

name: In pain
phrases_kaytetye: Nyarte ayenge ake artnweyenteyane, aherrkelarle ayenge ampenhe.
phrases_english: I'm paining in the head from the sun.

name: Headache
phrases_kaytetye: Ake ayenge arntetyawe, artnweyenteyane.
phrases_english: I've got a headache.

name: Mad
phrases_kaytetye: Artweye nthewarte angkentyelawe, akngwe nhartepe ilwekerange, aynewantheyenge akngwe nyartepe.
phrases_english: Don't talk about that man, he's mad, our poor relative.

name: Angry
phrases_kaytetye: Awelengkarle atewenhanthe althileyayne, awelengke inengele.
phrases_english: The angry people were fighting. They were an angry mob.

name: Homesick
phrases_kaytetye: Mpelarte altherarrenke ayenge alpewethe ayenge apmerarle.
phrases_english: I'm homesick I want to go back home.
